This place is amazing. My husband and I are huge fans of Cajun comfort food and this place did not disappoint. I got their Special: Cajun Shrimp Pot Pie. OH. MY. GOODNESS. AMAZING. So warm, comforting, and flavorful. I also got their begneit sampler for dessert. I found out that I personally am not a fan of crawfish, so I didn't like that one, but the original and the Chocolate ones were sooooooooo good. I wish I lived across the street from this place so I could come here every day.

We Ale Aires approximately 1 hour to get seated (we arrived around 1pm). The hostess was pleasant. Server came quickly to our table and took our drink orders; overall our server was very attentive. The drinks and food came in a timely manner and were temperature appropriate. We ordered a flight of beignet and they were pretty good. I ordered the shrimp and grits. Grits were a bit runny. Overall the experience was nice and we left full and satisfied.

I've always heard that SF was an awesome city for foodies, so for our first meal of our trip, we decided to check out Brenda's since it had an insane number of reviews. While walking here we noticed that the surrounding area was pretty sketchy, so we didn't really know what to expect. It turns out Brenda's is actually a pretty nice and clean spot and the food totally made it worth the trip. It reminded me of one of those hipster brunch spots in Chicago. The actual restaurant isn't that big so it was already full when we got there. You put your name on the chalkboard and just wait till they call you. While waiting we were looking through all the pictures on Yelp but were pretty disappointed to find out that a lot of the pictures were daily specials that weren't being offered on the day we went. There were so many great looking pics of different types of eggs benedict but unfortunately they weren't available. Either way, the food that we did order was still great. Chocolate Beignet - Super rich chocolate inside some fried dough. The chocolate center was so dense that it coated the inside of my mouth. Loved it. I made sure to save some of it for dessert at the end of the meal. Crawfish Beignet - More of a savory version of a beignet. I'm honestly not too big of a seafood fan, but cheese and cayenne pepper is a combo that can make anything taste really good. Hushpuppies - These were just okay. They were a little on the dry side and not much better than Long John Silvers. Shrimp and Grits - I always had the idea that grits were pretty bland and tasteless, but these grits were just delicious. They were some of the best grits I've ever had (basically only had it once before haha). The actual grits were creamy and buttery, the insane amount of cheese mixed in almost made the grits unrecognizable, and the super savory tomato bacon gravy poured on top just elevated it on another level of taste. The shrimp absorbed all the flavors of that gravy and were probably fresher than any shrimp I'm used to eating back home. Chicken Etouffee - Etouffee, jambalaya, gumbo...whatever you call it, I'm a fan of any sauce and rice combination. The chicken was moist and pull apart tender, and that tomato gravy was just so flavorful with a great balance of spicy and saltiness. Being Filipino, I love rice with everything so this was my kind of dish. Pulled Pork Po Boy - This was the daily special. I only had a little piece but that pulled pork was as tender as can be and it was a nice spin to the traditional po boy sandwich. Brenda's was definitely a cool spot to check out. Since almost everything on their menu sounded awesome, it was perfect to come here with a big group so we could try a little bit of everything.

You already know this place is delicious. Had the country fried steak and it was fantastic - I can't stop thinking about the gravy. We ordered appetizers but the waiter forgot to bring them out. When we told her she apologized and instead gave us another round of drinks so all was fixed. We went at 6pm on a Wednesday and it wasn't crowded at all, so if you're trying to avoid the lines give weeknights a try!

Hearing the hype about Brenda's, my friend and I decided to swing by for brunch on a Saturday. We arrived around 8am, right when it opened, and were seated promptly. We started with the flight of beignets: came with 4 kinds: plain (no stuffing), apple, chocolate, and crawfish. The plain beignet literally tasted like a donut, nothing particularly special. The apple one was good, was like a donut and apple pie combined. The crawfish was tasty but too salty for me to fully enjoy. And I didn't try the chocolate one to save room for the other dishes. Overall, it was a good choice to try and I recommend it if you like beignets. Next we had the shrimp and grits, which was very savory. The cheese and butter was very rich, and unfortunately quite oily and heavy. Nevertheless, it went extremely well with the shrimps, which were tender and fresh. This was a good choice, though it was really filling. We also ordered the andouille sausage and cheddar omelette. The omelette was good: the fluffiness of the egg went really well with the savory sausages and mushrooms. Though like the shrimp and grits, it was very heavy. The omelette also came with potatoes and a biscuit. The biscuit was alright but not particularly memorable. The potatoes were average - pretty bland and dry. I also ordered their cafe au lait. Their coffee had a decent taste but it was rather weak. These three dishes were extremely filling for two people, and we had to take the leftovers to-go. The service was good: our waitress was very attentive and nice, and the food came out fast. Overall, it was a good experience, though I don't think it lived up to its hype.

My first visit to Brenda's was a about two months ago, on a typical Saturday morning. The chicken and sausage gumbo is my second favorite. The roux was flavorful but it does not taste burnt. The chicken and sausage were also very tender enough so you know they have been in the pot long enough. The vegetables were also well cooked and seasoned. Those who dig donuts and fried pastries will love it! Since this is one of the most popular brunch place in the city, a long wait is inevitable, especially during the weekends. If you hate waiting in line, you should definitely come when they open because they don't take reservations.

    I've always heard that SF was an awesome city for foodies, so for our first meal of our trip, we decided to check out Brenda's since it had an insane number of reviews. While walking here we noticed that the surrounding area was pretty sketchy, so we didn't really know what to expect. It turns out Brenda's is actually a pretty nice and clean spot and the food totally made it worth the trip. It reminded me of one of those hipster brunch spots in Chicago.

    The actual restaurant isn't that big so it was already full when we got there. You put your name on the chalkboard and just wait till they call you. While waiting we were looking through all the pictures on Yelp but were pretty disappointed to find out that a lot of the pictures were daily specials that weren't being offered on the day we went. There were so many great looking pics of different types of eggs benedict but unfortunately they weren't available. Either way, the food that we did order was still great.

    Chocolate Beignet - Super rich chocolate inside some fried dough. The chocolate center was so dense that it coated the inside of my mouth. Loved it. I made sure to save some of it for dessert at the end of the meal.

    Crawfish Beignet - More of a savory version of a beignet. I'm honestly not too big of a seafood fan, but cheese and cayenne pepper is a combo that can make anything taste really good.

    Hushpuppies - These were just okay. They were a little on the dry side and not much better than Long John Silvers.

    Shrimp and Grits - I always had the idea that grits were pretty bland and tasteless, but these grits were just delicious. They were some of the best grits I've ever had (basically only had it once before haha). The actual grits were creamy and buttery, the insane amount of cheese mixed in almost made the grits unrecognizable, and the super savory tomato bacon gravy poured on top just elevated it on another level of taste. The shrimp absorbed all the flavors of that gravy and were probably fresher than any shrimp I'm used to eating back home.

    Chicken Etouffee - Etouffee, jambalaya, gumbo...whatever you call it, I'm a fan of any sauce and rice combination. The chicken was moist and pull apart tender, and that tomato gravy was just so flavorful with a great balance of spicy and saltiness. Being Filipino, I love rice with everything so this was my kind of dish.

    Pulled Pork Po Boy - This was the daily special. I only had a little piece but that pulled pork was as tender as can be and it was a nice spin to the traditional po boy sandwich.

    Brenda's was definitely a cool spot to check out. Since almost everything on their menu sounded awesome, it was perfect to come here with a big group so we could try a little bit of everything.

    Hearing the hype about Brenda's, my friend and I decided to swing by for brunch on a Saturday. We arrived around 8am, right when it opened, and were seated promptly.

    We started with the flight of beignets: came with 4 kinds: plain (no stuffing), apple, chocolate, and crawfish. The plain beignet literally tasted like a donut, nothing particularly special. The apple one was good, was like a donut and apple pie combined. The crawfish was tasty but too salty for me to fully enjoy. And I didn't try the chocolate one to save room for the other dishes. Overall, it was a good choice to try and I recommend it if you like beignets.

    Next we had the shrimp and grits, which was very savory. The cheese and butter was very rich, and unfortunately quite oily and heavy. Nevertheless, it went extremely well with the shrimps, which were tender and fresh. This was a good choice, though it was really filling.

    We also ordered the andouille sausage and cheddar omelette. The omelette was good: the fluffiness of the egg went really well with the savory sausages and mushrooms. Though like the shrimp and grits, it was very heavy. The omelette also came with potatoes and a biscuit. The biscuit was alright but not particularly memorable. The potatoes were average - pretty bland and dry.

    I also ordered their cafe au lait. Their coffee had a decent taste but it was rather weak.

    These three dishes were extremely filling for two people, and we had to take the leftovers to-go. The service was good: our waitress was very attentive and nice, and the food came out fast.

    Overall, it was a good experience, though I don't think it lived up to its hype.

    The only bad thing I have ever heard about Brenda's is that it is really difficult to get a table.

    With that in mind, I had a random Monday off of work and decided to head over for brunch. I was able to grab a seat at a counter without waiting (a table would have been a bit of a wait, but I'm sure much better than on a weekend.

    I got chicory coffee, the Beignet flight, and a side of bacon.

    The coffee was different, but good! I would have liked a refill at some point.

    The beignets were insanely good. I cut them in half to see the insides and to help their molten innards cool down a bit. In order of my preference:
    1. Crawfish - Super good
    2. Plain - Perfect balance of textures and flavors
    3. Apple - Really tasty
    4. Chocolate - Delicious but sooooo rich - it was overwhelming

    Bacon - perfect. Maybe cooked a minute too long for my tastes, but good.

    I will definitely be back - hopefully with friends to try other things that sounded good on the menu.

    Note: Some staff were a little bit rude and blustery / inattentive, others seem friendly and courteous.

    Brenda, girl you know brunch!
    I admit, I'm not much for breakfast but brunch I love! Maybe it's the mimosas, maybe it's the dessert options early in the morning, maybe it's the fried food. Regardless - Brenda's serves it all!
    To start, they not only had the classic OJ Mimosa - they had Guava! I repeat - they have GUAVA Mimosas. These Miami girls were more than thrilled. Two please!
    Moving along the menu, typically I don't think to order an appetizer during brunch but when I saw beignet's on the menu. Game over, get in my belly! We opted for the sampler, because why not just try them ALL! They have the traditional, always a winner; chocolate, made with Ghiradelli chocolate a SF staple; Granny Smith Apple, twist on the apple pie; Crawfish, wait what? They did say that Brenda's is soul food & I feel the NOLA influence. Stay with me on the crawfish, it's not too spicey & very good. I recommend eating that one first then going down the line to more sweet! Save the chocolate for last, it can be messy!
    Next up the main course, make sure you have room! I went for the southern twist on a classic. Eggs Benedict with fried chicken. YUM YUM YUM. Two poached eggs on cream biscuits with creole hollandaise (there is the NOLA again). I oped to have it with the grits but I regret not getting the hash! Fried chicken was crispy yet juicy and the southern flavors went perfectly with the brunch favorite!
    Glad to add this to my brunch rotation when I'm in town. And like all of the other great brunch spots in SF there is a wait but it's worth it!
